1
00:00:00,160 --> 00:00:08,440
You might be looking for new ways to improve your understanding of something you are studying.

2
00:00:07,900 --> 00:00:14,600
Perhaps you are seeking better methods to remember important information.

3
00:00:14,460 --> 00:00:25,760
One way to help you reach these goals is to try teaching – not as a job, but as a way to improve your own learning.

4
00:00:25,640 --> 00:00:31,760
In today’s Education Tips, we will explore how teaching could help your studies.

5
00:00:31,120 --> 00:00:43,140
Researchers and educators have been interested in the link between teaching and learning for quite some time.

6
00:00:43,080 --> 00:00:51,920
A 1982 study found that tutoring helped both the tutors and the people who studied with them.

7
00:00:51,620 --> 00:00:59,680
Tutoring means teaching one person or a very small group of students.

8
00:00:59,390 --> 00:01:15,080
“Like the children they helped, the tutors gained a better understanding of and developed more positive attitudes toward the subject matter covered in the tutorial program,” the researchers wrote.

9
00:01:14,680 --> 00:01:23,180
Attitude is a term that means the way you think or feel about something.

10
00:01:22,700 --> 00:01:35,420
Also in the 1980s, Jean-Pol Martin, a French teacher in Germany, developed a way of teaching that asked students to teach each other.

11
00:01:34,980 --> 00:01:49,220
Martin taught language classes, but he expanded his “Learning by Teaching” method, also called LdL, to include other subjects as well.

12
00:01:48,040 --> 00:01:55,760
More recent studies have looked at the link between teaching and memory.

13
00:01:55,660 --> 00:02:09,039
A 2013 study, which we briefly described in a previous Education Tips, found that teaching had a strong effect on understanding and learning.

14
00:02:08,940 --> 00:02:20,660
An important part of the study compared the learning results of people who actually taught a lesson to those who simply prepared but did not teach.

15
00:02:20,200 --> 00:02:39,580
“Overall, these findings suggest that when students actually teach the content of a lesson, they develop a deeper and more persistent understanding of the material than from solely preparing to teach,” the researchers wrote.

16
00:02:39,160 --> 00:02:48,040
Persistent is a term that means continuing beyond the usual or expected amount of time.

17
00:02:47,540 --> 00:02:56,460
Scientists have also explored the question of why teaching improves learning.

18
00:02:56,360 --> 00:03:08,220
A 2018 study suggests that teaching may help your learning because you have to remember the information you have learned as you continue to teach.

19
00:03:07,880 --> 00:03:12,460
Experts call this “retrieval.”

20
00:03:12,340 --> 00:03:20,440
The researchers wrote that “retrieval practice possibly causes the learning benefits of teaching.”

21
00:03:19,100 --> 00:03:27,200
Practice is a term that means to do something over and over again to become better at it.

22
00:03:27,000 --> 00:03:39,380
The basic idea is that if you want to improve your memory of what you have learned, you have to practice remembering that information.

23
00:03:39,100 --> 00:03:51,000
While retrieval may be one reason that teaching helps learning, there could be other reasons. The issue remains an open question.

24
00:03:50,820 --> 00:03:58,240
The good news is that there are many ways that you can improve your learning by teaching.

25
00:03:58,040 --> 00:04:05,440
One way might be to teach your family or friends about something that you are learning.

26
00:04:05,320 --> 00:04:12,720
For example, you could teach your parents about English grammar or vocabulary.

27
00:04:12,570 --> 00:04:19,899
You could also try teaching a younger person – perhaps a cousin, brother or sister.

28
00:04:19,680 --> 00:04:27,100
Try to make your lessons simple and clear, and ask them what they do not understand.

29
00:04:27,000 --> 00:04:37,780
The process of teaching and asking for feedback will help you realize that you may not understand some things as well as you thought you did.

30
00:04:37,480 --> 00:04:43,460
That is an important, necessary step in the learning process.

31
00:04:42,760 --> 00:04:53,320
Another idea is to imagine yourself describing a lesson to someone, or to write the lesson down.

32
00:04:53,140 --> 00:05:03,950
In the Guardian newspaper, David Robson suggests that you could write an email describing what you have learned in great detail.

33
00:05:03,940 --> 00:05:12,240
A final idea for those who like technology: You could record video of yourself teaching information.

34
00:05:12,140 --> 00:05:20,520
You could then send the lesson to friends or put it on YouTube or some other social media service.

35
00:05:20,320 --> 00:05:26,340
Give teaching a try and let us know if it improves your learning!

36
00:05:26,120 --> 00:05:27,140
I’m John Russell.
